  "description": "The Bekenstein-Hawking entropy is the entropy of a black hole, proportional to the area of its event horizon:\nSBH=kBc3A4Gℏ=kBA4lP2S_{BH} = \\frac{k_B c^3 A}{4 G \\hbar} = \\frac{k_B A}{4 l_P^2}where AA is the horizon area, kBk_B is Boltzmann\u0026rsquo;s constant, GG is Newton\u0026rsquo;s gravitational constant, ℏ\\hbar is the reduced Planck constant, cc is the speed of light, and lP=Gℏ/c3l_P = \\sqrt{G\\hbar/c^3} is the Planck length.\nJacob Bekenstein proposed in 1972-1973 that black holes must carry entropy, reasoning as follows: if a black hole had zero entropy, you could reduce the entropy of the universe by throwing high-entropy matter into it, violating the second law of thermodynamics. Bekenstein conjectured that the entropy is proportional to the horizon area. Hawking\u0026rsquo;s calculation of Hawking radiation in 1974 confirmed the proportionality and fixed the constant.\n",
